node.text:
Now that the new year is here I feel it’s important to share this with you so can all be aware of the abuse that these beautiful animals go through so people can take some cute photos during their vacation. .
hope this Video🎥 can open Your eyes👀 a bit and give you a perspective on "Animal Interaction“ you might never had before!🤷🏼‍♂️ It‘s all up to US (Humans) if we accept things like this or not! If we support these things or not! 😓
•
Please SHARE this Video and help us shine a light on this serious global🌍 problem‼️Together we CAN END Animal Cruelty & Slavery🐾⛓
•
Also tag at least 3 Friends in the comments so we can spread this message. .
.
Thank you @dean.schneider for all the work you’re doing!

node.text:
Dolomite Alps In Italy 🇮🇹 are just magical. Some tourists prefer to travel to the Dolomites during the summer, between May and September, when the weather is pleasantly warm and the mountains lively and colorful. Early spring, when crocuses, Alpine snowdrops and scented bushes of Daphne bloom through the melting snow, is equally beautiful.

🎥 @rebe.twosoles 
📍 Dolomites Italy

node.text:
San Francisco’s Lombard Street, 1975, Known as the “Crookedest Street in the World,” I lived at the top of this hill for about four months, I would see thousands of people come take pictures daily. Lombard Street is one of San Francisco’s most popular landmarks. Every year, scores of visitors walk or drive down its eight sharp hairpin turns.

It’s also one of the cities most scenic streets. It’s of course most known for the one-way block on Russian Hill between Hyde and Leavenworth Streets, where eight sharp turns are said to make it the most crooked street in the world. The design, first suggested by property owner Carl Henry and built in 1922, was intended to reduce the hill's natural 27 percent grade, which was too steep for most vehicles, and increase safety.

The segment today (pre-covid) normally sees around 250 vehicles per hour, with average daily traffic reaching 2630 vehicles in 2013. During peak times, vehicles have to wait up to 20 minutes to enter the Crooked Street segment, in a queue that can reach Van Ness Avenue.

Fun fact: Lombard St. is not even the “crookedest” street in San Francisco. That title technically belongs to Vermont Street between 20th and 22nd streets on Potrero Hill.

Source: www.sftravel.com
